                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3128: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-06-06T12:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 6, 1919, noon</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received June 7, 7.38 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your June 3, 3 p.m. Situation unchanged since last telegram May 31, 1 p.m.<note
                        n="38" xml:id="d396fn38">Probably refers to his undated telegram, <ref
                            target="#pg_429">p. 429</ref>.</note> Japanese Minister has never
                    proposed any action to me although when I asked him whether anything was being
                    done he also laid great emphasis on the irrelevant contention that American
                    soldiers had been in the Japanese concession. See my telegram of May 3 [<hi
                        rend="italic">13</hi>], 4 p.m.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
